# PEDAL (Cursor)

When the user works on features, planning, design/engineering docs, gap analysis, iteration, or completion reports, follow the **PEDAL** workflow defined in the repository.

## Canonical spec

Read and apply: **[.pedal/PEDAL.md](.pedal/PEDAL.md)**

It covers phases, directory layout, severity-weighted scoring, `.pedal-status.json`, templates under `.pedal/templates/`, and general rules (document language = user's prompt language, git conventions).

## How to invoke (natural language)

**Single phase** — map user intent to phase:

- Plan / planning / requirements → **plan**
- Engineering / design / spec / architecture doc → **engineering**
- Implement / build / code → **do** (code only; no separate PEDAL doc)
- Gap analysis / verify vs spec → **analyze**
- Auto-fix / iterate / improve until thresholds → **iterate**
- Wiki + report / close cycle / PR → **learn**
- Archive finished docs → **archive**

**Compound (multi-phase)** — run phases sequentially; each completes fully (cross-review + commit) before the next begins:

| Command   | Phases                             | Human approval gate                                       |
| --------- | ---------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| **spec**  | plan → engineering                 | ⛔ Pause after Engineering; wait for approval before `do` |
| **build** | do → analyze (+ iterate if needed) | ⛔ Pause after Analyze; wait for approval before `learn`  |
| **dev**   | plan → engineering → do → analyze  | Both gates above apply                                    |

> Natural language triggers for compound commands:
>
> - "plan and spec it out", "write the docs first" → **spec**
> - "implement and check", "build and verify" → **build**
> - "run the full cycle", "do everything up to learn", "full dev" → **dev**

## Cross-review (when Cursor is main agent)

When Cursor is the main agent authoring PEDAL documents, **Gemini CLI** acts as the reviewer. After each document-producing phase, run via shell:

```bash
gemini -p "Review the file {path_to_document}. Also read {path_to_prompt_log} for the user's original intent. You are a critical reviewer. Follow the protocol in .pedal/REVIEW.md. Write your review to {path_to_review_output}." -m flash
```

**Examples:**

```bash
# After Plan phase
gemini -p "Review docs/01-plan/user-auth.plan.md. Also read docs/01-plan/user-auth.prompt.md for original intent. You are a critical reviewer. Follow .pedal/REVIEW.md. Write review to docs/01-plan/user-auth.plan.review.md" -m flash

# After Engineering phase
gemini -p "Review docs/02-engineering/user-auth.engineering.md. Also read docs/01-plan/user-auth.prompt.md for original intent. You are a critical reviewer. Follow .pedal/REVIEW.md. Write review to docs/02-engineering/user-auth.engineering.review.md" -m flash
```

After receiving the review, **critically evaluate** each finding. Accept valid points, reject incorrect ones with justification. Do not blindly apply all suggestions. See `.pedal/REVIEW.md` for the full protocol.

## Cursor-specific

- **2-Tier State Management (Mandatory)**: All state updates must be performed using `scripts/pedal-sync.sh`. This ensures concurrency safety and syncs local runtime state with the Git-tracked `.pedal-status.shared.json`.
- **Convention Compliance (Mandatory)**: Always read `docs/wiki/CONVENTIONS.md` during Plan, Engineering, Do, and Analyze phases to ensure strict adherence to project standards.
- Do **not** auto-switch to "Plan Mode" or similar isolated modes when writing the Plan; stay in normal agent mode and report progress (see PEDAL.md **plan** section).
- Prefer reading `.pedal/PEDAL.md` at the start of a multi-step PEDAL task so steps stay aligned with the single source of truth.

